"""
MKT Context Commentary — 1 Kings chapters 20–21
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-1kings-20-21.py

Ch 20: Ahab and Ben-hadad — two sieges of Samaria and the Aphek campaign; anonymous
       prophets; the territorial-deity theology of the Arameans and YHWH's refutation;
       the ḥērem (devoted-thing) verdict and Ahab's treaty-release.
Ch 21: Naboth's vineyard — ANE land-inheritance law; Jezebel's misuse of legal process;
       Elijah's dynastic curse; Ahab's repentance and YHWH's delayed judgment.

Key ANE/historical context:
- 20:1: Ben-hadad II in Assyrian annals as "Adad-idri/Hadadezer of Damascus" — ironically
        Ahab's ally at the Battle of Qarqar (853 BCE) against Shalmaneser III
- 20:23: "gods of the hills" — standard ANE territorial-deity theology
- 20:31: ḥesed characterization of Israel's kings — unique in Kings
- 20:34: sûqôt/bazaar trading rights in Damascus — commercial diplomacy
- 20:42: ḥērem — holy-war devotion to destruction; Ben-hadad was YHWH's ḥērem
- 21:3: naḥălāh — ancestral inheritance; Lev 25:23 / Num 36 theology
- 21:10: bērak used euphemistically for "curse" (same as Job 1:11)
- 21:19: prophecy's partial vs. full fulfillment: 22:38 (Samaria) / 2 Kgs 9:25-26 (Jezreel)
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

KINGS1 = {
  "20": {
    "1": "<p>Ben-hadad king of Aram — this is Ben-hadad II, son of the Ben-hadad I who made the treaty with Asa of Judah (1 Kgs 15:18-20). His Aramaic name <em>Bar-Hadad</em> means 'son of Hadad,' the Aramean storm deity; the Assyrian annals of Shalmaneser III identify him as 'Adad-idri of Damascus' or 'Hadadezer.' The coalition of 32 kings (<em>šᵉlōšîm ûšnayim melek</em>) reflects the feudal structure of Iron Age Levantine politics: larger states had vassal kings who supplied troops and shared in plunder. The siege of Samaria is set sometime before the Battle of Qarqar (853 BCE), where Ahab and Ben-hadad fought as allies against Shalmaneser III — one of the great ironies of the period: enemies in 1 Kgs 20, coalition partners within a few years of the same reign.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Ben-hadad's use of messengers (<em>malʾāḵîm</em>) for the ultimatum is standard ANE diplomatic protocol; direct communication between hostile kings was mediated through official emissaries whose persons were protected by convention. The escalating message sequence (v2-6) follows the pattern of suzerain-to-vassal demands in ancient treaty literature, testing the vassal's submission before pressing for more.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The initial demand — silver, gold, best wives and children — is a comprehensive asset claim that essentially demands Ahab's complete personal submission and wealth. In ANE context, wives and children as tribute items signaled not merely economic transfer but symbolic ownership of the king's household and lineage. Comparable demands appear in Akkadian diplomatic correspondence where a weaker king is asked to 'give' his personal assets as acknowledgment of vassalage.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Ahab's initial compliance — <em>lᵉḵā ʾădōnî hammelek kᵉḏiḇrᵉḵā ʾănî wᵉḵol ʾăšer lî</em>, 'as you say, my lord the king — I and all I have are yours' — is full vassal-submission formula. The phrase 'my lord the king' (<em>ʾădōnî hammelek</em>) applied to Ben-hadad, rather than to YHWH, is a capitulation of both political and theological order: Ahab renders to a foreign king the comprehensive submission that Deuteronomy reserves for YHWH alone (Deut 10:12).</p>",
    "5": "<p>The second message escalates: beyond taking the assets, Ben-hadad's servants will physically search Ahab's palace and officials' houses and take whatever they please. The addition of the house-search (<em>ḥāpaś ûlāqaḥ</em> — search and take) represents a demand for Assyrian-style administrative penetration of the royal household, not just tribute payment. This crosses a line Ahab can no longer accept: passive tribute is one thing, having foreign soldiers rummage through the palace is a public humiliation that the elders will not tolerate (v7-8).</p>",
    "6": "<p>The threat — servants coming 'tomorrow at this time' (<em>kāʿēt māḥār</em>) — gives a specific deadline that intensifies the pressure. The phrase 'whatever is pleasing to their eyes' (<em>ḵol maḥᵃmaḏ ʿênêhem</em> — whatever their eyes desire) is the vocabulary of unchecked appetite; the same root appears in the Achan narrative (Josh 7:21) and the narrative of Eve in the garden (Gen 3:6), always marking the grasping desire that transgresses boundaries. Ben-hadad's servants seizing <em>maḥᵃmaḏ</em> from Ahab's household is the action of unchecked foreign power.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Ahab's consultation with the elders — 'see clearly how this man is bent on trouble' (<em>dᵉʿû nā wûrᵉʾû kî rāʿāh hûʾ mᵉḇaqqēš</em>) — invokes the council-of-elders structure present throughout the monarchic period. The <em>ziqnê hāʾāreṣ</em> (elders of the land) are the representative leadership of the free landowners; their role in political decision-making alongside the king reflects the Israelite tradition that the king's power was not absolute but negotiated with the traditional tribal leadership (cf. the elders' role in Saul's and David's coronations).</p>",
    "8": "<p>The elders' united response — 'do not listen and do not agree' (<em>lōʾ tišmaʿ wᵉlōʾ tōʾbeh</em>) — validates Ahab's instinct and provides the political cover he needs to refuse. The distinction between the first demand (which Ahab accepted, v4) and the second (which the elders reject) is politically logical: tribute in principle is negotiable, but house-search is a violation of territorial sovereignty. The elders are defending their own interests as property-holding landowners: if foreign servants can search the palace, the precedent threatens their households too.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Ahab's diplomatic response draws a precise line: everything in the first message he agreed to, the second he cannot. The careful distinction between compliance-in-principle and refusal-in-practice is diplomatic language designed to avoid total rupture while refusing the escalation. The messengers carry back the refusal as instructed — the protocol of diplomatic correspondence is maintained even in defiance.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Ben-hadad's oath — 'may the gods deal severely with me if the dust of Samaria will be enough for each of my troops to take a handful' — is an ANE imprecatory formula invoking divine sanction on the swearer if the stated action fails. The hyperbole (implying such a vast army that Samaria's rubble would not even provide a handful per man) is military rhetoric designed to intimidate; it also echoes the 'as the dust of the earth' scale-of-defeat imagery used of overwhelming military victory. The reference to 'the gods' (<em>kōh-yaʿᵃśûn lî ʾelōhîm wᵉḵōh yōsîpû</em>) is the standard Aramean oath form, parallel to the 'So may YHWH do to me and more' formula used by Israelites (19:2).</p>",
    "11": "<p>Ahab's proverb — <em>lōʾ yithallēl ḥōgēr kᵉmapattēaḥ</em>, 'let not the one who straps on his armor boast like one who takes it off' — is one of the few proverbial sayings attributed to a king in the historical books. The proverb contrasts pre-battle boasting with post-battle reality: the one girding for battle (beginning the fight) should not claim the confidence of the one who has already fought and survived. It is a pointed rebuke of Ben-hadad's premature victory celebration. Comparable battle-wisdom sayings appear in Egyptian and Mesopotamian wisdom literature warning against premature confidence before an engagement is decided.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Ben-hadad's location — drinking in the <em>sukkôt</em> (field shelters, campaign booths) with his 32 vassal kings — is the detail that explains the Israelite victory. The military headquarters is a drinking party; the command structure is relaxed. His response to Ahab's proverb is to issue formation orders (<em>śîmû</em>), but the army takes positions slowly. Field shelters or campaign booths (<em>sukkôt</em>) were temporary structures erected for a siege camp; Ben-hadad's comfortable drinking in them while the siege continues suggests he expected no resistance requiring active command.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The anonymous prophet who approaches Ahab — unnamed, unlike Elijah and Elisha — is part of a distinctive pattern in 1 Kgs 20-22 where YHWH's word comes through unnamed prophets rather than named ones. This may reflect the prophetic guild structure (the <em>bᵉnê hanᵉḇîʾîm</em>, 'sons of the prophets') that appears more formally in 2 Kings. The oracle formula — 'thus says the LORD: Do you see this great army? I am giving it into your hand today, and you will know that I am the LORD' — is the self-revelation formula of the Exodus tradition: YHWH acts in history so that the recognition 'I am YHWH' follows. The theological point is that the coming victory is YHWH's war, not Ahab's military competence.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The battle plan — attack using the <em>naʿarê śārê hamᵉdînôt</em> (young men/attendants of the provincial governors), with Ahab opening the engagement — is tactically unusual: it deploys a secondary administrative force rather than the standing military units. The 'district governors' (<em>śārê hamᵉdînôt</em>) are the administrative officials of Israel's provincial structure (cf. 1 Kgs 4:7-19, Solomon's twelve district officers); their attendants were the administrative staff of the royal provinces. Using this non-military force is both tactically surprising and theologically appropriate: the victory will be visibly YHWH's rather than the professional army's.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The force numbers — 232 attendants of provincial governors plus 7,000 Israelite troops — are explicitly small against Ben-hadad's coalition. The 7,000 number echoes 1 Kgs 19:18 (the 7,000 in Israel who had not bowed to Baal) — whether this is the same group is not stated, but the number creates a literary resonance: the remnant of YHWH's faithful people is exactly the force he uses to deliver Israel. Against 32 kings with horses and chariots (v1), a few thousand men and 232 attendants is the kind of disproportion that marks YHWH's hand in the victory.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The noon attack catches Ben-hadad and the 32 kings mid-feast (<em>šōteh šikkôr basukkôt</em> — drinking drunk in the field shelters). The noon hour is the most exposed and least combat-ready time — the army has relaxed after the morning and before any afternoon alert; the leadership is inebriated. The vulnerability of drunken commanders is a recurring narrative element in Israel's holy wars: the Midianites are asleep when Gideon strikes (Judg 7); the Philistines are celebrating when Samson attacks (Judg 16). The motif emphasizes that the enemy's defeat is YHWH's judgment on their hubris.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Ben-hadad's scouts report 'men coming out of Samaria' — ambiguously, since such a small force (232 men) would not immediately register as a battle formation. The ambiguity leads to Ben-hadad's confused order (v18): take them alive whether they come for peace or war, suggesting he doesn't yet recognize the 232 as the opening of a military attack. The scouts' report triggers an intelligence failure on Ben-hadad's part that the text presents as divinely orchestrated.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Ben-hadad's 'take them alive whether for peace or war' (<em>im lᵉšālôm yāṣᵉʾû tipmᵉʾûm lᵉšālôm wᵉʾim lᵉmilḥāmāh yāṣᵉʾû lᵉḥayyîm tipmᵉʾûm</em>) is a double-instruction that assumes any Israelite force is small enough to capture. The order is a tactical error: it sends men to take prisoners rather than to repel an attack, preventing the Arameans from forming a proper defensive line before the main Israelite force (v19) follows the 232 out. The prisoner-capture order becomes the context for the flight that follows.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The double-force structure — the 232 attendants as vanguard, with the seven-thousand Israelite army behind them — is tactically coherent: the small vanguard draws out Ben-hadad's response, and the main force follows to exploit the confusion. The Arameans are already engaged in prisoner-taking (v18 order) before they realize a full army is behind the 232.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The battle account — 'each man struck down his opponent' (<em>wayyakkû ʾîš ʾîšô</em>) — uses the idiom of individual combat rather than massed battle; the phrasing may reflect a rout in which the Arameans are caught individually rather than in formation. Ben-hadad's escape 'on horseback with some cavalry' (<em>wayyimlāṭ melek ʾărām ʿal-sûs wᵉpārāšîm</em>) demonstrates the collapse of his command: the king flees with a personal cavalry escort while his coalition disintegrates.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Ahab's capture of horses and chariots and 'great defeat' of Aram (<em>maggēpāh gᵉḏôlāh</em>) reverses the military calculus: Israel's inferior force defeats Aram's 32-king coalition. The capture of horses and chariots is specifically significant because Deuteronomy 17:16 warns against the king multiplying horses for himself; Ahab's accumulation of captured Aramean equipment is not commented on, but the detail registers against the Deuteronomistic framework.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The anonymous prophet returns after the battle with a strategic warning: 'Go, strengthen yourself, take note of what you need to do, for at the turn of the year the king of Aram will attack you again.' The phrase 'turn of the year' (<em>lᵉtᵉšûḇat haššānāh</em>) is the technical term for spring, the military campaigning season in the ancient Levant — once the winter rains ended and roads became passable. The prophet's warning allows Ahab time to prepare; the divine foreknowledge that will bring the second Aramean force is already in play.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The Aramean servants' military-theological analysis — 'their gods are gods of the hills (<em>ʾelōhê hārîm hēmmāh</em>), that is why they overpowered us; but if we fight them in the plain we will certainly be stronger' — is a textbook example of ANE territorial-deity theology. The standard assumption was that deities had jurisdictional limits: mountain deities were powerful in their terrain, less so on flat ground. The Arameans are extrapolating from the hill country of the Samarian highlands (where Samaria stood) to conclude that moving to Aphek's plain (v26) would neutralize YHWH's advantage. This assumption is theologically precise from a pagan standpoint and precisely wrong from the Deuteronomistic one: YHWH's transcendence over topography is a constant theme (Ps 121:2: 'my help comes from the LORD, who made heaven and earth'; Isa 40:12 — he measures the mountains in scales).</p>",
    "24": "<p>The Aramean tactical reform — replacing the 32 kings with professional military commanders (<em>paḥôt</em>, officers/provincial commanders) — reflects a real organizational evolution. The feudal coalition of 32 kings with their own armies and loyalties was both a strength (numbers) and a weakness (conflicting command structures, competing interests). Professional military governors under a single chain of command would produce better coordination. The advice is militarily sound; the defeat will be theological, not tactical.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The plan to match Israel 'horse for horse, chariot for chariot' and fight in the plain shows the Arameans have analyzed the previous defeat tactically but missed its theological cause. The numerical replacement — rebuilding the army exactly to previous strength — is the ANE military logic of quantitative parity. YHWH's forthcoming rebuke (v28) specifically addresses the theology of the tactical analysis: it is not the terrain or the numbers that decided the first battle.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Aphek (identified with Tell en-Nasbeh east of the Sea of Galilee, or possibly a site in the plain east of Samaria) is chosen precisely because it is in the plain rather than the hill country — the Arameans are acting on their territorial-deity analysis. The spring campaign timing confirms the seasonal pattern the prophet warned about (v22). Ben-hadad's personal leadership of the remobilized army ('he went up to Aphek') shows that despite the first defeat he remained in command; the throne coup that will eventually remove him (2 Kgs 8:7-15, by Hazael) has not yet occurred.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The visual contrast — 'the Israelites camped opposite them looking like two small flocks of goats, while the Arameans covered the land' (<em>ûḇᵉnê Yiśrāʾēl... hayyô wayhî kišnê ḥaśpê ʿizzîm wᵉʾărām milᵉʾû ʾet hāʾāreṣ</em>) — is one of Kings' most vivid military images. The goat-flock comparison makes explicit what the numbers imply: Israel is hopelessly outnumbered by visible measurement. The contrast sets up the divine intervention that follows: YHWH wins with what appears to be insufficient force, just as Gideon's 300 against Midian (Judg 7) and the boy David against Goliath (1 Sam 17) established as the pattern of YHWH's war-theology.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The oracle of the man of God directly addresses the Aramean theology: 'Because the Arameans have said, YHWH is a god of the hills and not a god of the valleys, I will give all this great army into your hand, and you will know that I am YHWH.' The self-revelation formula — <em>ûyᵉḏaʿtem kî ʾănî YHWH</em> — is the climactic point. YHWH fights in the plain precisely to refute the territorial-deity theology, not just to help Israel. His honor is at stake in the battle; the Arameans' false theology becomes the occasion for a theological demonstration. The same logic governs the Exodus plagues (Exod 7:5: 'the Egyptians shall know that I am YHWH') — YHWH's actions in history are both deliverance for his people and revelation of his character to the nations.</p>",
    "29": "<p>The seven-day face-off before battle — 'they camped across from each other for seven days' — may reflect standard siege or challenge protocol in ANE warfare, where a formal battle might be preceded by a period of positioning and psychological pressure. The seventh-day battle has symbolic resonance with the seven-day completion pattern of creation and covenant; in Joshua the seventh circuit of Jericho on the seventh day precipitates the walls' fall (Josh 6). The 100,000 Aramean infantry killed in a single day (<em>ûḇᵉyôm ʾeḥāḏ wayyakků ḇᵉnê Yiśrāʾēl</em>) is a war-narrative hyperbole expressing total victory, comparable to the numbers in the wilderness census or the Deuteronomistic battle accounts.</p>",
    "30": "<p>The collapse of the Aphek city wall on 27,000 survivors is presented as an additional divine act completing the military victory. The specificity of the number (27,000 — precisely stated, not a round figure) may reflect an archival source with actual casualty estimates from both battles. Ben-hadad's flight into 'an inner room of an inner room' (<em>ḥeḏer bᵉḥāḏer</em> — a room within a room, the innermost and most concealed space available) echoes the Elijah/Elisha motif of inner rooms: the hiding king discovers the same vulnerability that Ben-hadad's initial assault on Samaria was designed to exploit (v5-6: his servants would search 'every room').</p>",
    "31": "<p>The servants' advice — 'we have heard that the kings of the house of Israel are kings of <em>ḥesed</em>' (<em>kî malkê bêt Yiśrāʾēl kî malkê ḥesed hēm</em>) — is the only place in the entire Deuteronomistic History where Israel's kings are characterized by <em>ḥesed</em> (steadfast loyalty, covenant-love) as a recognized institutional virtue. The Aramean servants are drawing on a diplomatic reputation: Israel's kings have a known pattern of showing mercy to defeated enemies rather than executing them. The sackcloth and ropes (<em>śaqqîm... ḥăḇālîm ʿal rōʾšênû</em>) are the ANE submission-posture for petitioning the victor's mercy — sackcloth as mourning/humility, ropes around the neck as a symbol of surrender.</p>",
    "32": "<p>Ben-hadad's petition — 'Your servant Ben-hadad says, please let me live' — and Ahab's response 'Is he still alive? He is my brother' (<em>ʾaḥî hûʾ</em>) is the narrative crux of ch 20. The word 'brother' (<em>ʾāḥ</em>) is the kinship vocabulary of treaty relationships in the ancient Levant; Ahab's servants use it in the Amarna archive, and the Egyptian-Hittite treaty uses fraternal language for the two great kings. By calling Ben-hadad 'my brother,' Ahab invokes the diplomatic-treaty framework rather than the holy-war framework. The prophetic parable of vv35-42 will identify this choice as a fatal substitution: treating YHWH's <em>ḥērem</em> (devoted enemy) as a treaty-partner.</p>",
    "33": "<p>The servants 'were watching carefully for a sign' (<em>wayhannᵉšû waymahrû wayyaḥᵃlᵉṭû himmennû</em> — literally 'they interpreted it as an omen and quickly caught hold of it from him') — the Hebrew idiom suggests the servants were looking for any positive cue from Ahab that they could lock into. The word 'brother' was the sign; they immediately amplified it: 'Your brother Ben-hadad!' Ahab's response — 'Go, bring him' — then Ben-hadad being brought up into the chariot — is the full reception of a defeated king as an equal. Bringing him into the chariot makes them chariot-companions, the highest symbolic position of military fellowship.</p>",
    "34": "<p>The treaty terms: return of cities Aram's previous king had taken from Israel (probably under Ben-hadad I), plus establishment of Israelite trading quarters (<em>ḥûṣôt</em> — bazaars, trading streets) in Damascus, reciprocating the Aramean bazaars Ben-hadad I had established in Samaria. Commercial treaty rights in a foreign capital city were standard in the ancient Levant: the Assyrian merchant colonies in Anatolia (Kültepe/Kaneš, c. 1900 BCE) are the best-documented example, but bazaar rights in Iron Age cities appear in treaty texts from Mesopotamia. Ahab's response — 'I will release you with this covenant' — makes the treaty explicit: Ben-hadad is released under a formal covenant agreement (<em>bᵉrît</em>), not simply pardoned.</p>",
    "35": "<p>The parable sequence begins with one of the 'sons of the prophets' (<em>bnê hanᵉḇîʾîm</em>) requesting a companion to strike him — by the word of the LORD (<em>bᵉḏaḇar YHWH</em>). The refusal to strike, despite the divine command conveyed through the prophet, results in immediate death by lion. The son-of-prophets guild — groups of prophetic disciples associated with established prophets (Elijah, Elisha) — appears frequently in 2 Kings (2:3, 5, 7, 15; 4:1; 5:22; 6:1; 9:1). The incident establishes two things: that obedience to a divine word communicated through a recognized prophet carries the same obligation as a direct divine command, and that prophetic speech-acts (like the strike-and-wound sequence) are not merely symbolic performances but activated realities.</p>",
    "36": "<p>The lion-killing for disobedience parallels the story of the man of God from Judah (1 Kgs 13:24-26) who was killed by a lion for disobeying a divine command. The pattern — divine command → disobedience → lion as divine agent of judgment — is a recognizable Kings trope. In both cases, the lion-death is explicitly presented as YHWH's judicial execution for specific prophetic disobedience, not random predation.</p>",
    "37": "<p>The second man's willingness to strike and wound the prophet enables the parable-performance to proceed. The wounding (<em>wayyakkēhû wᵉhakkēh</em>) is real, not symbolic: the prophet's disguise requires an actual wound to be plausible. The pain of the prophet's enacted parable mirrors the pain of the prophetic message itself; Jeremiah and Ezekiel also perform painful sign-acts (Jer 13; Ezek 4-5). The willingness of the second man to obey the command (even without knowing its purpose) contrasts with the first man's refusal.</p>",
    "38": "<p>The prophet disguises himself with a bandage over his eyes — a wound-dressing that marks him visually as a returning soldier. Waiting along the road for the king's passage is the standard approach for petitioners who lacked court access; the king's road-journey created a rare public moment when ordinary people could petition directly. The disguise is necessary because the prophet is about to deliver a parable in which a soldier violated a command: Ahab must render judgment before knowing the parable is about himself.</p>",
    "39": "<p>The parable the prophet tells: a soldier was entrusted with guarding a prisoner with his life (a <em>ḥērem</em>-equivalent: 'your life for his life, or you will weigh out a talent of silver'). The prisoner escaped while the soldier was 'busy here and there' (<em>hāyāh ʿaḇdᵉḵā ʿōśeh hēnnāh wāhēnnāh</em>). The talent of silver is an enormous sum (c. 34 kg) — a punitive fine that would reduce a man to debt-slavery; the life-for-life alternative is execution. The legal framework invokes the principle that an escaping prisoner's guardian bears full liability; military law throughout the ancient Near East held guards responsible for their prisoners.</p>",
    "40": "<p>The king's verdict — 'your sentence is decided; you have judged it yourself' (<em>kēn mišpāṭeḵā ʾattāh ḥāraṣtā</em>) — is the trap of the judicial parable genre. The same structure appears in Nathan's parable of the poor man's sheep (2 Sam 12:1-7) and in Jesus' parable of the vineyard owner (Luke 20:9-16): the hearer renders judgment on a parable, then discovers the parable is about himself. The genre exploits the fact that hearing a story about someone else produces objective moral judgment unclouded by self-interest; the revelation that the parable is self-referential makes the hearer's own verdict binding.</p>",
    "41": "<p>The prophet removes the bandage quickly — the word <em>wayᵉmahēr wayyāsar ʾet hāʾăpēr mēʿal ʿênāyw</em> (he quickly removed the bandage from his eyes) is a stripping-away of disguise that is also a stripping-away of Ahab's self-deception. The king 'recognized him as one of the prophets' (<em>wayyakkîrēhû melek Yiśrāʾēl kî min hanᵉḇîʾîm hûʾ</em>) — the recognition is immediate once the disguise is removed. The prophetic identity, once revealed, transforms the context: Ahab is not hearing a soldier's legal case but a divine oracle.</p>",
    "42": "<p>The oracle — 'because you released the man I had devoted to destruction (<em>heḥĕramtî</em>), your life will be for his life and your people for his people' — turns on the term <em>ḥērem</em>. In Deuteronomic holy-war theology, <em>ḥērem</em> designated an enemy devoted to complete destruction as YHWH's property: no prisoners, no plunder, no treaties. The same principle applied to the Canaanite nations (Deut 7:2) and to Saul's incomplete execution of Agag (1 Sam 15), where Saul's failure to enforce <em>ḥērem</em> cost him the kingdom. Ahab has repeated Saul's error: releasing a king YHWH had designated for destruction in exchange for treaty-benefits. The verdict is proportional — Ben-hadad's life for Ahab's life, Aram's people for Israel's — signaling the military defeats that will follow.</p>",
    "43": "<p>Ahab returns to Samaria <em>sar wᵉzāʿēp</em> — 'resentful and angry' — the same phrase used in 21:4 after Naboth's refusal. The compound characterization is Ahab's signature emotional response to prophetic challenge: not repentance but sullen resentment. The phrase frames the two episodes as parallel: in both, a divine word confronts Ahab's misuse of power and sovereignty, and in both, his response is sullen anger rather than covenant obedience. The resentment of ch 20 and ch 21 is the emotional precursor to the choices that will cost him his life (1 Kgs 22:34-38).</p>"
  },
  "21": {
    "1": "<p>Naboth the Jezreelite's vineyard 'adjacent to the palace of Ahab king of Samaria' — the geographical detail matters. Jezreel (Tell Jezreel / Tel Yizre'el) in the Jezreel Valley was where Ahab had a second royal residence alongside his Samarian palace; the Jezreel palace was probably a military-administrative base overlooking the strategically vital valley. The proximity of Naboth's vineyard to the royal estate makes it both desirable and coveted — and makes the conflict between the king's desire and the commoner's ancestral right unavoidable. <em>naḥălāh</em> (ancestral inheritance) is mentioned explicitly in the story three times (vv3, 4, 6), establishing it as the theological center of the conflict.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Ahab's initial request is framed as reasonable — he offers a better vineyard elsewhere or fair market price. The offer reflects a king who at this point is still operating within a framework of negotiated transaction rather than royal seizure. His characterization of the vineyard as a <em>gan yārāq</em> (vegetable garden) — a functional, practical use — is notably prosaic: he wants productive land near the palace for royal kitchen use, not trophy acquisition. The reasonableness of the initial offer makes Naboth's refusal more pointed and Jezebel's response more extreme.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Naboth's refusal — <em>ḥālîlāh lî mêYHWH mittittî naḥălat ʾăḇōtay lāk</em>, 'YHWH forbid that I should give you my ancestral inheritance' — invokes the core Levitical land theology. Lev 25:23-28 establishes that the land ultimately belongs to YHWH ('the land shall not be sold permanently, for the land is mine; for you are strangers and sojourners with me'); land within a family's tribal allotment could be redeemed by a kinsman-redeemer and must revert in the jubilee year. Numbers 36:7-9 reinforces that each tribe's inheritance must remain within the tribe. Naboth is not being stubborn or greedy — he is citing a principle that makes selling the family inheritance an act of theological betrayal, not merely a personal preference. His refusal is a matter of covenant law, not negotiation.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Ahab's response — going home <em>sar wᵉzāʿēp</em> (resentful and sullen, exactly as in 20:43), lying on his bed, turning his face to the wall, and refusing to eat — is royal petulance that commentators from Josephus onward have noted. The posture (face to the wall, refusing food) is the ANE posture of deep grief or terminal illness (compare Hezekiah in 2 Kgs 20:2 turning his face to the wall in prayer before recovery). Ahab's position is between grief and rage; his inability to eat signals a genuine emotional crisis rather than performative sulking. But the crisis is entirely self-created: he wants what the law forbids him to take.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Jezebel's question — 'why is your spirit so troubled that you will not eat?' — positions her as the household manager inquiring after the king's welfare. The Phoenician princess who brought Baal worship to Israel (16:31-33) is now the one who resolves the problem of Naboth's refusal. Her role in the story is not merely enabling Ahab's desire but supplying what the Deuteronomistic narrative treats as a foreign understanding of royal power: in Phoenician political culture, a king's rights over property were not limited by the kind of ancestral-inheritance protections the Mosaic law built into Israelite land tenure.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Ahab's retelling of the Naboth episode to Jezebel edits the exchange: he omits Naboth's theological reason for refusing ('YHWH forbid') and reports only 'I will not give you my vineyard.' The omission is significant — whether Ahab fails to understand the theological weight of Naboth's answer, or whether he understands it and chooses not to communicate it to Jezebel, the result is the same: Jezebel hears only a commoner's refusal of a royal request, not a covenant-law invocation.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Jezebel's question — 'Do you not now govern Israel?' (<em>ʾattāh ʿattāh taʿᵃśeh mamlākāh ʿal Yiśrāʾēl</em>) — articulates a concept of kingship foreign to the Deuteronomic law. In the surrounding cultures, the king was the sovereign landowner; Mesopotamian legal tradition from Hammurabi onward gave kings broad powers to requisition property for royal needs, compensating at market rates or below. The Deuteronomic restriction (Deut 17:14-20: the king shall not multiply horses, wives, or silver; he shall write a copy of the Torah and not exalt himself above his brothers) sharply limited the king's power precisely to prevent royal acquisitiveness of the sort Jezebel is now proposing. Jezebel's challenge to Ahab's authority is really a challenge to the entire Israelite political-theological framework.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Jezebel's use of Ahab's name, seal, and royal authority — writing letters in his name and sealing them with the royal seal — is legally appropriate and morally fraudulent. The royal seal authenticated official correspondence throughout the ancient Near East; clay or wax sealings impressed with the king's seal were legally binding. Jezebel's forgery is technically complete: the letters have the right form, the right seal, the right name. The fraud is in the content and intent, not the formal elements. The recipients — elders and nobles of Jezreel — have no way to know the letters do not represent Ahab's genuine will.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The letter's instructions — proclaim a fast and seat Naboth in the place of honor — use the mechanisms of covenant-community self-governance against themselves. A public fast was a communal response to perceived sin or divine judgment (cf. Joel 2:12-15; Jonah 3:5); by proclaiming one, Jezebel implies there is a covenant offense in the community requiring investigation and atonement. The seating of Naboth in the 'place of honor' (<em>rōʾš hāʿām</em>, head of the people) is the accused's position before a judicial assembly — honor and suspect in the same moment, under the community's examination.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The instruction to place two 'sons of belial' (<em>bnê beliyyaʿal</em> — worthless men, scoundrels) as witnesses echoes Deuteronomy 17:6 and 19:15-21's requirement of two witnesses for capital cases. Jezebel's legal strategy cynically fulfills the letter of the two-witness rule while violating its spirit: the witnesses are perjurers, not credible community members. The charge — 'Naboth has cursed God and the king' (<em>bēraḵ ʾelōhîm wāmelek</em>) — uses the verb <em>bāraḵ</em> (bless) as a euphemism for 'curse' (<em>qillēl</em>); the same euphemism appears in Job 1:5, 11 and 2:5, 9, where Job's wife tells him to 'bless God and die.' The charge combines blasphemy (capital, Lev 24:16) and treason (capital) into a death-penalty case.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The compliance of the elders and nobles — 'just as Jezebel had instructed in the letters she had sent' — is the civic failure the narrative condemns alongside Ahab's passivity and Jezebel's scheming. The community leaders who were supposed to be the guardians of covenant justice (Deut 16:18-20: appoint judges who do not pervert justice, take bribes, or show partiality) execute the judicial murder without recorded objection. The silence of the community's leaders in the face of obvious injustice is the systemic failure that makes individual crimes possible.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The fast is proclaimed and Naboth is placed in the assembly's position of prominence. The civic machinery of covenant community — the public fast for communal examination, the public seating of the accused — is mobilized for its opposite purpose. The legitimate form of covenant community justice becomes the instrument of covenant community murder.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The execution follows the legal requirements precisely: two witnesses testify before the assembly, Naboth is 'taken outside the city and stoned to death.' Stoning outside the city (Lev 24:14, 23; 1 Kgs 21:13) was the required form for blasphemy; removing the condemned person from the city both physically and symbolically excluded them from the covenant community before execution. Every procedural element is correct; the entire process is judicial murder. The precise legal compliance makes the sin worse, not better: the law's protective mechanisms have been turned into weapons against the person they were meant to protect.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The report to Jezebel — 'Naboth has been stoned and is dead' — triggers her immediate message to Ahab. The speed of the report (from Jezreel to Samaria or from the assembly to the palace) and the efficiency of Jezebel's response suggest she had been waiting for exactly this message. The death is presented as a fait accompli that Ahab had no part in planning and perhaps no specific knowledge of — a deniability structure. He asked for the vineyard; Jezebel arranged its acquisition; the blood is not formally on Ahab's hands, but YHWH's oracle will hold him accountable regardless (v16, 19).</p>",
    "15": "<p>Jezebel's instruction to 'arise and take possession of the vineyard of Naboth the Jezreelite who refused to sell it to you, for Naboth is not alive but dead' conflates the two crimes the prophet will identify in v19: murder and seizure. The phrasing 'who refused to sell' retroactively reframes Naboth's legal-theological refusal as mere commercial obstinacy — the official Omride court version of events. The emphasis 'not alive but dead' (<em>lōʾ ḥay kî mēt</em>) is blunt: the obstacle has been removed; property law is now the only consideration.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Ahab's arising and going down to Naboth's vineyard to 'take possession' (<em>lārešet ʾōtāh</em>) of it is his formal act of acquisition — the legal completion of Jezebel's scheme. Under ANE property law, the death of the owner without male heirs (Naboth's sons are killed alongside him according to 2 Kgs 9:26) reverted property to the crown in some jurisdictions; Jezebel's scheme has created the legal condition for royal acquisition that Naboth's living refusal prevented. Ahab may understand the possession as legal; YHWH's view (v19) is that it is seizure after murder.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The divine commissioning of Elijah — 'the word of the LORD came to Elijah the Tishbite' — uses the standard prophetic-call formula. Elijah's reappearance after the ch 19 Horeb theophany and his commissioning to find Elisha (19:15-16) marks his resumption of active prophetic ministry. The brevity of the commissioning notice — no vision, no elaborate call — contrasts with the Horeb encounter's full narrative; the word simply comes, and Elijah goes.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The divine geographic direction — 'go down to meet Ahab king of Israel who is in Samaria; he is in Naboth's vineyard where he has gone to take possession of it' — gives Elijah precise intelligence that serves both a practical and theological function. Practically, Elijah knows exactly where to find Ahab. Theologically, YHWH's knowledge of exactly where Ahab is and exactly what he is doing at that moment underlines the divine omniscience that Ahab's act cannot escape: there is no deniability before YHWH even if there is legal deniability before human courts.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Elijah's oracle — 'Have you murdered and also seized?' (<em>hārāṣaḥtā wᵉgam-yārāštā</em>) — collapses the two crimes into a single indictment. The 'and also' (<em>wᵉgam</em>) is prosecutorial: both crimes are named, both are attributed to Ahab despite his indirect role. The blood-licking prophecy — 'in the place where dogs licked up the blood of Naboth, dogs will lick your blood too' (<em>bimqôm ʾăšer lāqᵉqû haḵlāḇîm ʾet dam Nāḇôt yālᵉqû haḵlāḇîm ʾet-dāmᵉḵā gam ʾattāh</em>) — is spatially specific. The partial fulfillment comes in 22:38: 'they washed the chariot at the pool of Samaria, where the prostitutes bathed, and the dogs licked up his blood' — dogs lick Ahab's blood, but in Samaria, not Jezreel. The fuller fulfillment comes in 2 Kgs 9:25-26: Jehu throws Joram's corpse into Naboth's plot in Jezreel, citing this very oracle. Both texts engage the question of where exactly the prophecy was fulfilled, suggesting the community of readers was aware of the spatial discrepancy and considered it significant.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Ahab's greeting — 'Have you found me, my enemy?' (<em>hamᵉṣāʾtanî ʾōyᵉḇî</em>) — is his consistent posture toward Elijah: the prophet is the king's enemy, not his counselor. Elijah's response — 'I have found you because you have sold yourself to do evil in the sight of the LORD' (<em>ʾămāṣāʾtîḵā yaan hithmaḵerḵā laʿᵃśôt hārāʿ bᵉʿênê YHWH</em>) — introduces the 'sold himself' (<em>māḵar ʾet napšô</em>) language that the Deuteronomist uses as Ahab's defining characterization (v25 repeats it: 'there was none who sold himself to do evil as Ahab did'). The commercial metaphor of self-sale suggests voluntary, complete self-commitment to evil — the inverse of covenant loyalty.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The dynastic destruction oracle — 'I will bring disaster on you and will utterly sweep you away' (<em>mēḇîʾ ʾēlêḵā rāʿāh ûḇiʿartî ʾaḥᵃrêḵā</em>) — uses <em>biʿēr</em> (consume, sweep away, clear out), the same verb used for Israel's obligation to 'remove evil' from its midst (Deut 13:5, 17:7, 17:12, 19:19 — always <em>ûḇiʿartā hārāʿ</em>). The oracle turns the Deuteronomic purging-evil language back on Ahab: his house is the evil to be removed from Israel. The cutting off of 'every male, slave or free, in Israel' (<em>kol maštin bqîr ʿāṣûr wᵉʿāzûḇ bᵉYiśrāʾēl</em>) uses the idiom for complete male-line extermination previously applied to the houses of Jeroboam (1 Kgs 14:10) and Baasha (1 Kgs 16:11).</p>",
    "22": "<p>The explicit comparison — 'your house like the house of Jeroboam son of Nebat and like the house of Baasha son of Ahijah' — places Ahab in the line of northern dynasty-destroyers. Jeroboam's house was exterminated by Baasha (1 Kgs 15:29); Baasha's house was exterminated by Zimri and then Omri (1 Kgs 16:11-12). Ahab's house will be exterminated by Jehu (2 Kgs 9-10). The pattern is explicitly the Deuteronomist's: the sin-provocation-destruction cycle repeats with each northern dynasty. The charge 'you have provoked me to anger and led Israel into sin' makes Ahab's judgment parallel to Jeroboam's (1 Kgs 14:9, 16) and Baasha's (1 Kgs 16:7) in both offense and consequence.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Jezebel's oracle — 'the dogs shall eat Jezebel in the plot of ground at Jezreel' (<em>haḵlāḇîm yōʾḵᵉlû ʾet Yizᵉḇel bᵉḥēleq Yizrᵉʿel</em>) — is geographically precise: Jezreel, the site of Naboth's vineyard, is where she will die. The fulfillment in 2 Kgs 9:30-37 is one of the most detailed in Kings: Jehu orders her thrown from the window, horses trample her, and when servants come to bury her they find only her skull, feet, and hands — the dogs have eaten everything else. Jehu's comment (2 Kgs 9:36-37) cites this very oracle. The 'plot of ground at Jezreel' (<em>ḥēleq Yizrᵉʿel</em>) in the fulfillment narrative is Naboth's very field (2 Kgs 9:25) — the crime site becomes the execution site.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The extension of the dynastic curse to all of Ahab's house — city dogs for those who die in the city, birds for those who die in the open country — echoes the curse on Jeroboam's house (1 Kgs 14:11) and Baasha's house (16:4) in virtually identical language. The repeated formula links the three failed northern dynasties into a single pattern of divine judgment on apostate kings. Death without burial — consumed by scavengers — was the ultimate dishonor in the ancient Near East: it meant no memorial, no proper passage to the realm of the dead, and the total erasure of the person's existence. The denial of burial is itself a prophetic curse on the house's pretension to dynastic permanence.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The Deuteronomist's parenthetical verdict — 'there was no one like Ahab who sold himself to do evil in the sight of the LORD, stirred up by Jezebel his wife' (<em>raq lōʾ hāyāh kᵉʾaḥʾāḇ ʾăšer hitmaḵar laʿᵃśôt hārāʿ bᵉʿênê YHWH ʾăšer hissᵉtāh ʾōtô ʾîzāḇel ʾištô</em>) — is the absolute superlative of negative evaluation. 'No one like' is the Deuteronomist's extreme comparison (used positively for Josiah in 2 Kgs 23:25: 'no king like him before or after'). The attribution 'stirred up by Jezebel his wife' is the Deuteronomist's analysis of the mechanism: Ahab's evil was incited by his foreign wife's initiative. This does not absolve Ahab — the oracle addresses him directly as the responsible party — but it identifies Jezebel as the instigator of the most egregious acts.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The comparison to 'the Amorites who the LORD drove out before Israel' returns to the Conquest logic of 2 Kgs 17:8: the nations were driven out for their wickedness; Israel adopts the same wickedness and incurs the same judgment. <em>gillûlîm</em> (idols, the polemical term with probable dung-imagery) is the same term used in 2 Kgs 17:12 and throughout Ezekiel. Ahab's idol-following — specifically attributed to Jezebel's influence in 1 Kgs 16:32-33 (building a temple and altar for Baal in Samaria) — is here classified with Amorite abomination, the most severe category of covenant-violation in the Deuteronomistic framework.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Ahab's repentance at Elijah's oracle is unique in Kings: the tearing of clothes, sackcloth next to the skin, fasting, and going about in mourning (<em>wayyiqraʿ ʾet bᵉgāḏāyw wayyāśem śaq ʿal bᵉśārô wayyāṣom wayyiškaḇ baśśāq wayhallēk āṭ</em>) constitute the full ANE mourning and repentance posture. The detail 'sackcloth next to his skin' (<em>ʿal bᵉśārô</em>) — rather than over outer clothing — indicates the most radical form of self-abasement, the rough cloth abrading the skin as a physical embodiment of grief and penitence. For the man who killed Naboth and took his vineyard to now fast and wear sackcloth is extraordinary; the Deuteronomist records it without editorializing.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The divine word comes again to Elijah after Ahab's repentance — a second divine response in the same chapter, showing the dynamic quality of YHWH's engagement with his covenant people. The prophetic word is not simply predictive fate but a real-time response to human action. The structure of vv27-29 exactly mirrors the prophetic pattern in Jonah (3:4-10: Jonah declares disaster; Nineveh repents; God relents) and anticipates the theological principle of Jeremiah 18:7-10: when YHWH speaks disaster and the people turn from evil, YHWH will relent from the planned disaster.</p>",
    "29": "<p>The divine response to Ahab's humbling — <em>yaʿan kî niḵnāʿ mippānay lōʾ ʾāḇîʾ hārāʿāh bᵉyāmāyw bᵉyamê bᵉnô ʾāḇîʾ hārāʿāh ʿal bêtô</em>, 'because he has humbled himself before me, I will not bring the disaster in his days; in his son's days I will bring the disaster on his house' — is theologically remarkable on several counts. First, genuine repentance from YHWH's worst-rated king produces a real divine response: the disaster is delayed, not merely symbolically acknowledged. Second, the delay is personal, not dynastic: Ahab himself is spared the destruction he brought on his house. Third, the shift to Ahab's son positions the Jehu coup (2 Kgs 9-10) as the fulfillment deferred, not averted. The grace extended to Ahab does not nullify the judgment on the house; it demonstrates that YHWH responds to repentance even from the most compromised position, with real consequences for timing if not ultimate outcome.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('mkt-context', '1kings')
    merge_comm(c, KINGS1)
    save_comm('mkt-context', '1kings', c)
    count = sum(len(v) for v in KINGS1.values())
    print(f'1kings mkt-context: wrote {count} verses across ch 20-21')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
